window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>1","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : BASIC CONCEPT OF ECONOMICS","question":"Which of the following is central to the definition of Economics?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Resources","B":"Wants","C":"Scarcity","D":"Capital"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Scarcity is central to the definition of Economics. Economics is the study of how individuals, businesses, governments, and societies make choices to cope with scarcity. Scarcity refers to the basic economic problem, the gap between limited resources and theoretically limitless wants.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>2","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : INTRODUCTION","question":"When the production possibility curve shifts outwards, the economy experiences","images":[],"options":{"A":"growth","B":"over-population","C":"ineffiecient use of resources","D":"under-population"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The production possibility curve (PPC) represents the maximum combination of goods and services that can be produced by an economy with the available resources and technology. An outward shift of the PPC represents economic growth, as it means that the economy can now produce more of both goods and services than before. This could be due to an increase in resources or an improvement in technology.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>3","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : FACTORS OF PRODUCTION","question":"Land as a factor of production is made useful through the","images":[],"options":{"A":"application of human effort","B":"acts of nature","C":"application of fertilzer","D":"use of machines"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Land as a factor of production becomes useful through the application of human effort. This includes activities such as farming, mining, and construction. While acts of nature, application of fertilizer, and use of machines can enhance the productivity of land, it is the application of human effort that primarily makes land useful as a factor of production.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>4","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC SYSTEM : ECONOMIC PROBLEMS OF THE SOCIETY","question":"In a free market economy, resources are allocated through the","images":[],"options":{"A":"government department","B":"price mechanism","C":"trade union","D":"state planning committee"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a free market economy, resources are allocated through the price mechanism. The price mechanism is the system in a free market economy where decisions about what to produce, how to produce, and for whom to produce are made based on the prices of goods and services. Prices are determined by the forces of supply and demand. If demand for a product increases, its price will rise, which will incentivize producers to produce more of that product. Conversely, if demand for a product decreases, its price will fall, which will discourage producers from producing that product.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>5","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS : SCIENTIFIC APPROACH","question":"Use Figure 1 below to answer questions below          The diagram in Figure 1 above depicts a","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"simple bar chart","B":"complex bar chart","C":"component bar chart","D":"multiple bar chart"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A component bar chart is used when the data involved are of two variables each component is represented by a section proportional in size to its representation in total of each bar","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>6","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Figure 2 below shows change in demand for commodity X which is a normal good.Use it to answer thne questions that follows          Which of the following caused the change in demand from D1D1 to D2D2?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Fall in the income of consumers","B":"Rise in the price of a substitute","C":"Rise in the price of a complement","D":"Fall in the supply of commodity X"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A change in the demand from D0 D0 to D2 D2 is caused by the rise in the price of substitue i.e if the price of milo increases, consumers will buy more of Bournvita which will make the demand for Bournvita to increase.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>7","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : SUBSIDY","question":"Use Figure 3 below to answer the question that follows.        The curves Do Do and So So are the initial demand and supply curves respectively.What happens when government provides subsidy to producers?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"The supply curve will shift from SoSo to S2 S2","B":"The supply curve will shift from SoSo to S1S1","C":"The demand curve will shift from DoDo to D1D1","D":"The supply curve will shift from S1S1 to SoSo"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When the government feels that the market price for the producers is too low, it decides to pay them subsidy.Subsidy shifts the supply curve downward to the right. From the diagram above, the supply will curve will shift from S0 S0 to S2 S2","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>8","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : CONCEPT OF MARKET AND PRICE","question":"In Figure 4 above,YZ represents","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"excess demand","B":"excess supply","C":"equilibrium quantity","D":"equilibrium price"},"answer":"B","explanation":"From the diagram above, YZ represent excess supply since it is above the equilibruim price","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>9","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : TYPES OF DEMAND","question":"Goods are described as inferior if their demand","images":[],"options":{"A":"decreases as price falls.","B":"increases as income rises.","C":"decreases as income increases.","D":"increases as price increases."},"answer":"C","explanation":"Inferior goods are those goods for which demand decreases when consumer income increases. This is because as income increases, consumers shift to more expensive or higher quality substitutes. Therefore, the correct answer is 'decreases as income increases.'","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>10","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM","question":"A consumer is in equilibrium when","images":[],"options":{"A":"his market supply is equal to his market demand.","B":"he maximizes his satisfaction from spending his income","C":"the market is also in equilibrium.","D":"he has consumed all he wants"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A consumer is said to be in equilibrium when he maximizes his satisfaction given his income and the market prices. This is based on the concept of utility maximization, which states that consumers aim to get the most satisfaction (utility) possible from their spending, given their budget constraints. Therefore, the correct answer is 'he maximizes his satisfaction from spending his income.'","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>11","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Goods that are abundant in supply usually have low","images":[],"options":{"A":"total utility.","B":"marginal utility.","C":"average utility.","D":"time utility."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Marginal utility refers to the additional satisfaction a consumer gains from consuming one more unit of a good or service. If a good is abundant in supply, it means that the additional satisfaction gained from consuming one more unit of the good (marginal utility) is likely to be low because the consumer has already consumed a lot of it. Therefore, the correct answer is 'marginal utility.'","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>12","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : DISTINCTION BETWEEN CHANGE IN QUANTITY SUPPLIED AND CHANGE IN SUPPLY","question":"An increase in supply means that","images":[],"options":{"A":"more is sold at different prices.","B":"more is sold at same price","C":"there is leftward shift of the supply curve.","D":"there is a movement along the supply curve."},"answer":"A","explanation":"An increase in supply means that producers are willing and able to sell more of a good or service at each price. This is often due to factors such as improvements in technology, an increase in the number of producers, or a decrease in the cost of production. Therefore, 'more is sold at different prices' is the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>13","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : TYPES OF SUPPLY","question":"If an increase in the price of crude oil led to an increase in the prices of kerosene and  grease,then kerosene and grease are in","images":[],"options":{"A":"joint supply.","B":"competitive supply.","C":"market supply.","D":"composite supply."},"answer":"A","explanation":"When an increase in the price of one good (in this case, crude oil) leads to an increase in the supply of other goods (in this case, kerosene and grease), those goods are said to be in joint supply. This is because they are produced together or are by-products of the same production process. Therefore, 'joint supply' is the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>14","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : ELASTICITY OF SUPPLY","question":"A seller increased the quantity he offered for sales from 200 units to 250 units when price of his product increased by 12.5%.What is the price elasticity of supply of his product?","images":[],"options":{"A":"2.00","B":"1.50","C":"1.00","D":"0.50"},"answer":"A","explanation":"e  = % \u2206 in Qs/% \u2206 in price    % \u2206 in Qs = 250 - 200/200 x 100                = 50/200 x 100  = 25%    Since the % \u2206 in p =12.5     Therefore, ep = 25/12.5   = 2","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>15","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : TYPES OF SUPPLY","question":"If an increase in the supply of beef increased the supply of hides,then beef and hides are in","images":[],"options":{"A":"competitive supply.","B":"joint supply.","C":"composite supply.","D":"joint demand."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Beef and hides are in joint supply. This is because an increase in the supply of beef leads to an increase in the supply of hides. Joint supply refers to a situation where an increase in the production of one good leads to an increase in the supply of another good. In this case, when more beef is produced, more hides are also produced as a by-product.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>16","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY","question":"If a beef market is in equilibrium at $4.00 per kg,an increase in price to $6.00 per kg may cause","images":[],"options":{"A":"surplus in the market.","B":"shortage in the market.","C":"black market to come into operation.","D":"rationing to be introduced."},"answer":"A","explanation":"If a beef market is in equilibrium at $4.00 per kg, an increase in price to $6.00 per kg may cause a surplus in the market. This is because at a higher price, quantity supplied will exceed quantity demanded. This situation is known as a surplus. In other words, producers are willing to supply more at the higher price, but consumers are not willing to buy as much, leading to an excess supply or surplus.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>17","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : PRODUCERS EQUILIBRIUM","question":"A large firm may experience diseconomies of scale if there is","images":[],"options":{"A":"difficulty in coordinating  decisions.","B":"division of labour in production.","C":"employment of more specialists.","D":"decrease in the cost of production."},"answer":"A","explanation":"A large firm may experience diseconomies of scale if there is difficulty in coordinating decisions. Diseconomies of scale occur when a firm's long-run average costs start to rise as output increases. This can happen in large firms due to problems with communication and coordination. As firms grow larger, it can become more difficult to manage and coordinate the firm's operations, leading to inefficiencies and higher costs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>18","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : PRODUCTION FUNCTIONS AND LAWS OF RETURNS","question":"Increasing returns to scale suggests that","images":[],"options":{"A":"a firm can make profit by reducing output.","B":"a firm can make more profit by increasing output","C":"as the producer reduces the quantity of raw materials used,the marginal product will double.","D":"as the producer increases the quantity of raw materials used,the marginal product will fall."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Increasing returns to scale refers to a situation where a firm can increase its output more than proportionately by increasing all its inputs. This means that if a firm doubles its inputs, its output will more than double, leading to more profit. Therefore, the correct answer is 'a firm can make more profit by increasing output'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>19","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : THE CONCEPT OF REVENUE","question":"One feature of the average fixed cost is that it","images":[],"options":{"A":"falls continuously but is never equal to zero.","B":"is U-shaped and intersects the Y-axis.","C":"rises and falls faster than the marginal cost.","D":"is always higher than the average variable cost."},"answer":"A","explanation":"Average Fixed Cost (AFC) is the fixed cost of production divided by the quantity of output produced. As output increases, AFC decreases because the same fixed cost is spread over more units of output. However, it never reaches zero because fixed costs are costs that do not change with the level of output. Therefore, the correct answer is 'falls continuously but is never equal to zero.'","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>20","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : THE CONCEPT OF REVENUE","question":"If the average fixed cost (AFC) of producing 5 bags of rice is $20.00,the average fixed cost of producing 10 bags will be","images":[],"options":{"A":"$2.00","B":"$4.00","C":"$10.00","D":"$20.00"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Average Fixed Cost (AFC) is calculated by dividing the total fixed cost by the quantity of output. If the AFC of producing 5 bags of rice is $20.00, then the total fixed cost is $100.00 ($20.00 * 5). If the firm produces 10 bags of rice, the AFC will be $10.00 ($100.00 / 10). Therefore, the correct answer is '$10.00'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>21","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : THE CONCEPT OF REVENUE","question":"Table 1 below shows the total revenue schedule of a firm. Use the information to answer the question                                                                         Table 1  Output(Units)            5060708090Total revenue(TR) $  85102119136153    What is the units price of the firm's output?","images":[],"options":{"A":"$10.00","B":"$2.70","C":"$2.00","D":"$1.70"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The unit price of the firm's output is calculated by dividing the total revenue by the number of units. For example, at 50 units, the total revenue is $85. So, the unit price is $85/50 = $1.70.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>22","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : THE CONCEPT OF REVENUE","question":"Table 1 below shows the total revenue schedule of a firm. Use the information to answer the question                                                                         Table 1  Output(Units)            5060708090Total revenue(TR) $  85102119136153  What is the firm's marginal revenue?","images":[],"options":{"A":"$153.00","B":"$17.00","C":"$1.70","D":"$0.80"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Marginal revenue =  \u2206 in total revenue/\u2206 in output                                   =  102 - 85/ 60 - 50                                        =      17 /10                                                                                     = 1.7","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>23","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : CO-OPERATIVE SOCIETIES~~BUSINESS ORGANISATION : SOLE PROPRIETOSHIP~~BUSINESS ORGANISATION : PARTNERSHIP~~BUSINESS ORGANISATION : PUBLIC CORPORATIONS","question":"Organization and entreprenuership are vested in different persons in a","images":[],"options":{"A":"cooperative society","B":"sole proprietorship","C":"partnership","D":"public company"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In a public company, organization and entrepreneurship are vested in different persons. The entrepreneurs (shareholders) provide the capital and bear the risk, while the organization (management) runs the business.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>24","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : PUBLIC CORPORATIONS","question":"The public sector in a mixed economy is  not  always efficient because of","images":[],"options":{"A":"bureacratic practices","B":"the desire to make huge profit","C":"annual planning of activities","D":"the activities of shareholders"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The public sector in a mixed economy is not always efficient due to bureaucratic practices. Bureaucracy often involves a lot of red tape, slow decision-making processes, and inefficiencies due to the lack of competition and profit motive. The other options do not accurately describe the reasons for inefficiency in the public sector.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>25","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE WHOLESALER","question":"Which functions of the wholesaler enables him to stabilize prices?","images":[],"options":{"A":"warehousing goods","B":"advertising the goods","C":"granting credit to retailers","D":"transporting goods"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The function of the wholesaler that enables him to stabilize prices is warehousing goods. By warehousing goods, wholesalers can control the supply of goods in the market, releasing them when there is high demand and storing them when there is low demand, thereby stabilizing prices. The other options do not directly contribute to price stabilization.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>26","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : SUPPLY OF LABOUR","question":"In the long run, as individual receives higher wages, it causes","images":[],"options":{"A":"demand for food to decrease","B":"demand for leisure to decrease","C":"supply of normal goods to decrease","D":"supply of labour to decrease"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the long run, as an individual receives higher wages, it causes the supply of labour to decrease. This is because as wages increase, individuals may choose to work fewer hours, effectively reducing the supply of labour. The other options do not accurately describe the effects of higher wages in the long run.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>27","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"POPULATION : DETERMINANTS OF POPULATION SIZE","question":"Population growth rate can be calculated as","images":[],"options":{"A":"birth rate- death rate-emigrants-immigrants","B":"birth rate-death rate+migration rate-immigration rate","C":"birth rate- death rate","D":"birth rate- death rate + immigrants - emigrants"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Population growth rate is calculated as the birth rate minus the death rate plus the net migration (immigrants - emigrants). This is because the population increases with births and immigrants (people moving into the area) and decreases with deaths and emigrants (people moving out of the area).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>28","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : DEMAND FOR LABOUR","question":"Labour productivity is defined as","images":[],"options":{"A":"output per man hour","B":"average output","C":"the maximum number of hours worked","D":"total output of labour"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Labour productivity is defined as output per man hour. It is a measure of the efficiency of a worker or group of workers performing a task. It is calculated by dividing the total output by the total number of man-hours. It is not the average output, the maximum number of hours worked, or the total output of labour.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>29","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : FEATURES","question":"Which of the following problems has the least effect on agricultural productivity in West Africa?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Incidence of pests and diseases","B":"Unfavourable weather conditions","C":"Urban-rural migration","D":"Illiteracy"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Urban-rural migration has the least effect on agricultural productivity in West Africa. This is because the other options, such as the incidence of pests and diseases, unfavourable weather conditions, and illiteracy, have a more direct and significant impact on agricultural productivity. Urban-rural migration can even potentially increase agricultural productivity if the migrants bring new skills and knowledge to the rural areas.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>30","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"The location of iron and steel industry at a place is due to","images":[],"options":{"A":"easy access to raw material","B":"access to cheap labour","C":"government policy","D":"good infrastructure"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The location of iron and steel industry at a place is primarily due to easy access to raw materials. Iron and steel industry is a heavy industry that requires large quantities of heavy and bulky raw materials such as iron ore, coal, and limestone. The cost of transporting these materials can be high, so industries often choose to locate near the source of raw materials to reduce transportation costs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>31","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"Import substitution as a strategy of industrialization is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"replacement of locally produced goods with imported ones","B":"development of local firms to produce local goods that are imported","C":"establishement of firms to process imported raw materials","D":"act of using local inputs to produce goods for export"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Import substitution as a strategy of industrialization is the development of local firms to produce goods that are imported. The idea behind this strategy is to reduce dependency on foreign goods and promote the growth of domestic industries. This strategy was widely used by developing countries in the mid-20th century to promote their industrial sectors.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>32","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : INTRODUCTION","question":"Which of the following are intermediate products?","images":[],"options":{"A":"cement and steel","B":"furniture and shirt","C":"handkerchief and shoe","D":"table and door"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Intermediate products are those products that are used as inputs in the production of other goods. They are not final goods and are used in the production process of other goods. Cement and steel are examples of intermediate products as they are used in the construction industry to produce buildings and other structures. Furniture, shirts, handkerchiefs, shoes, tables, and doors are all final goods, not intermediate products.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>33","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : MEASUREMENT OF NATIONAL INCOME","question":"How is NNP at factor cost derived from GNP at market prices?","images":[],"options":{"A":"GNP - Depreciation + Indirect taxes + Subsidies","B":"GNP - Depreciation - Indirect taxes + Subsidies","C":"GNP + Depreciation + indirect taxes - Subsidies","D":"GNP + Depreciation - Indirect taxes + SUbsidies"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Net National Product (NNP) at factor cost is derived from Gross National Product (GNP) at market prices by subtracting depreciation and indirect taxes, and adding subsidies. This is because depreciation is the wear and tear of capital goods which should be deducted from GNP. Indirect taxes increase the market price hence should be subtracted, while subsidies reduce the factor cost hence should be added.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>34","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : PROBLEMS OF NATIONAL INCOME","question":"Which of the following factors may lead to under-estimation of national income figures?","images":[],"options":{"A":"availability of skilled statisticians","B":"high volume of exports","C":"emigrations of skilled workers to foreign countries","D":"subsistence production"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Subsistence production may lead to under-estimation of national income figures. This is because subsistence production refers to the production of goods for personal consumption and not for sale in the market. As such, these goods are often not counted in the calculation of national income, leading to an underestimation of the true economic activity in a country.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>35","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INFLATION & DEFLATION : CAUSES & CONTROL","question":"Inflation may occur if","images":[],"options":{"A":"rate of productivity is higher than wage rate","B":"prices fluctuate during a particular season of the year","C":"wage increase is granted without increase in productivity","D":"the government embarks on restrictive monetary policies"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Inflation may occur if wage increase is granted without an increase in productivity. This is because when wages are increased without a corresponding increase in productivity, it means that the cost of production has increased. If the cost of production increases, producers may pass on this cost to consumers in the form of higher prices, leading to inflation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>36","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"MONEY : VALUE OF MONEY","question":"Money would cease to be good store of value when","images":[],"options":{"A":"prices of goods and services are fallng slowly","B":"there is high level of unemployment","C":"prices of goods and services are rising rapidly","D":"prices of goods and services are rising slowly"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Money would cease to be a good store of value when prices of goods and services are rising rapidly. This is because inflation erodes the purchasing power of money. When prices rise rapidly, the value of money falls as it can buy fewer goods and services. This makes it a poor store of value.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>37","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INFLATION & DEFLATION : CAUSES & CONTROL","question":"Governments in West Africa can curtail inflation by","images":[],"options":{"A":"purchasing securities in the open market","B":"selling securities in the open market","C":"encouraging importation of goods from all countries","D":"encouraging banks to lead for consumption"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Governments in West Africa can curtail inflation by selling securities in the open market. This is a monetary policy tool known as open market operations. When the government sells securities, it reduces the amount of money in circulation, which helps to reduce inflation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>38","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"The central bank can reduce the ability of commercial banks to give out loans by","images":[],"options":{"A":"raising the bank rate","B":"reducing special deposit","C":"reducing the liquidity ratio","D":"issuing more currency"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The central bank can reduce the ability of commercial banks to give out loans by raising the bank rate. The bank rate is the interest rate at which the central bank lends money to commercial banks. When this rate is increased, it becomes more expensive for commercial banks to borrow money from the central bank, which reduces their ability to give out loans.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>39","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"Tools of monetary policy do not inculde","images":[],"options":{"A":"open market operations","B":"reserve requirement","C":"bank rate","D":"tax and public expenditure"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Monetary policy is the macroeconomic policy laid down by the central bank. It involves management of money supply and interest rate and is the demand side economic policy used by the government of a country to achieve macroeconomic objectives like inflation, consumption, growth and liquidity. The tools of monetary policy include open market operations, reserve requirement, and bank rate. Tax and public expenditure are tools of fiscal policy, not monetary policy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>40","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : FISCAL POLICY","question":"During inflation, the appropriate fiscal measure to adopt is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"increase indirect taxes","B":"increase direct taxes","C":"reduce personal income tax","D":"increase government expenditure"},"answer":"B","explanation":"During inflation, the appropriate fiscal measure to adopt is to increase direct taxes. Inflation is a general increase in prices and fall in the purchasing value of money. By increasing direct taxes, the disposable income of individuals decreases which in turn reduces their purchasing power. This can help to control inflation as it reduces demand for goods and services.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>41","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : PRINCIPLE OF TAXATION","question":"Mr. X and Mrs. Y pay $500.00 and $1,400.00 as taxes on their earnings of $5,000.00 and $7,000.00 respectively. The system of taxation employed is","images":[],"options":{"A":"specific tax","B":"proportional tax","C":"regressive tax","D":"progressive tax"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The system of taxation employed is regressive tax. A regressive tax is a tax applied uniformly, taking a larger percentage of income from low-income earners than from high-income earners. It is in opposition to a progressive tax, which takes a larger percentage from high-income earners. In this case, Mr. X pays 10% of his earnings as tax while Mrs. Y pays 20% of her earnings as tax. Therefore, the tax is regressive as it takes a larger percentage from the lower income earner.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>42","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT : DEVELOPMENT PLANNING","question":"Expenditure on food takes a large proportion of incomes of people in","images":[],"options":{"A":"Industrialized countries","B":"advanced countries","C":"developing countries","D":"capitalist countries"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Expenditure on food takes a large proportion of incomes of people in developing countries. This is because in developing countries, a significant portion of income is spent on basic needs such as food, clothing, and shelter. In contrast, in industrialized or advanced countries, a smaller proportion of income is spent on food as income levels are generally higher and basic needs are more easily met.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>43","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : TERMS OF TRADE","question":"A country should embark on development planning to ensure that","images":[],"options":{"A":"it becomes popular among the comity of nations","B":"it also do what others are doing","C":"its scare productive resources are efficiently utilized","D":"the nation is able to contribute its own quota to international organizations"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A country should embark on development planning to ensure that its scarce productive resources are efficiently utilized. Development planning is a strategic plan for economic development that aims to improve the economic and social well-being of a community. It involves the allocation of limited resources, such as labor, capital, and natural resources, in a way that maximizes the production of goods and services. This helps to ensure that resources are not wasted, but are used in the most efficient way possible.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>44","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : TERMS OF TRADE","question":"A country is allowed to import just 50,000 tonnes of rice annually.  This describes","images":[],"options":{"A":"devaluation","B":"tariff","C":"embargo","D":"quota"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A country is allowed to import just 50,000 tonnes of rice annually. This describes a quota. A quota is a type of trade restriction that sets a physical limit on the quantity of a good that can be imported during a specific period. It is used to protect domestic producers from competition by limiting the amount of foreign goods that can enter the country.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>45","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : PRINCIPLES OF INTERNATIONAL TRADE","question":"Dumping is selling goods in a foreign market at a price","images":[],"options":{"A":"below what is sold at the home market","B":"above what is sold at the home market","C":"equal to what is sold at the home market","D":"equal to the cost of producing the goods"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Dumping is a term used in the context of international trade. It's when a country or company exports a product at a price that is lower in the foreign importing market than the price in the exporter's domestic market. Hence, the correct answer is 'below what is sold at the home market'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>46","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : ECONOMIC INTEGRATION IN AFRICA","question":"The principle of comparative advantage encourages a country to","images":[],"options":{"A":"produce only consumer goods","B":"engage in trade if its can produce a commodity at a lower cost","C":"specialize in the production of all goods","D":"try as much as possible to be self - sufficient"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The principle of comparative advantage suggests that a country should engage in trade if it can produce a commodity at a lower opportunity cost than other countries. It doesn't mean that the country should produce only consumer goods or all goods, or try to be self-sufficient. Rather, it should specialize in producing and exporting only those goods and services which it can produce more efficiently.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>47","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC ORGANISATION : IBRD, AFDB, UNCTAD ETC","question":"In order to discourage the importation of manufactured goods, a country should adopt","images":[],"options":{"A":"import promotion strategy","B":"export led strategy","C":"liberal foreign exchange","D":"import substitution strategy"},"answer":"D","explanation":"To discourage the importation of manufactured goods, a country should adopt an 'import substitution strategy'. This strategy encourages domestic industries to produce goods that the country would otherwise import. This reduces dependency on foreign goods and strengthens the domestic manufacturing sector.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>48","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : INTRODUCTION","question":"A free trade area is one in which","images":[],"options":{"A":"each member operates its own barriers against non-members","B":"factors of production are mobile","C":"members adopts a common external tariff against non-members","D":"members adopt common fiscal and economic policies"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A free trade area is a region where a group of countries has signed a free trade agreement, and they do not impose tariffs, quotas or other trade barriers on each other. However, each country in the free trade area maintains its own trade policies, including tariffs and other trade barriers, with countries outside the free trade area. Therefore, the correct answer is 'each member operates its own barriers against non-members'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>49","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC ORGANISATION : IBRD, AFDB, UNCTAD ETC","question":"The foremost objective of the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"help promote private and public investments","B":"assist members achieve balance of payments stability","C":"grants long term loan for infrastructure","D":"maintain stabilty of foreign exchange"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) is a global development cooperative owned by 189 member countries. The foremost objective of the IBRD is to reduce poverty in middle-income and creditworthy poorer countries by promoting sustainable development through loans, guarantees, risk management products, and analytical and advisory services. Therefore, the correct answer is 'help promote private and public investments'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2020>50","subject":"Economics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : INTRODUCTION","question":"The exploitation of mineral resources constitutes which form of production?","images":[],"options":{"A":"primary production","B":"secondary production","C":"tertiary production","D":"services production"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The exploitation of mineral resources is a form of primary production. Primary production refers to the sector of an economy that involves the extraction and harvesting of natural resources. It includes activities such as mining, agriculture, forestry, fishing, and quarrying. Therefore, the correct answer is 'primary production'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];